{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280602061/1937111501/0009.xml":{"full_text":"11,500 PAY BILL\nBill Also Provides Small In\ncreases for Workers Un\nder $3,600 Figure.\nViator McCarran, Democrat, of\nNevada, came back for the special\nsession today, prepared to make re\nnewed efforts on behalf of his Govern\nment pay bill, which would fix $1,500\nas the minimum for full-time service\nwith smaller increases for other em\nployes who are not receiving more\nthan $3,600 a year.\nThere also is pending a separate\nmeasure confined to raising the low\nest brackets up to a $1,200 minimum,\nwithout any changes above that point,\nwhich :s generally regarded as the\nadministration's answer to the Mc\nCarran proposal.\nThe Nevadan said today he still be\nlieves his $1,500 minimum should be\nadopted, contending that govern\nmental agencies have referred to\nthat as the amount required to main\ntain American standards of living.\nIf he cannot obtain enactment of\nhis proposal he indicated he will ac\ncept the $1,200 figure as a last resort.\n\u201cEven if it is decided $1,200 is the\nminimum that should .be allowed, I\nstill think my bill should be consid\nered with that minimum substituted\nfor the $1,500 figure, because my bill\nis broader in scope, including an im\nproved procedure for dealing with effi\nciency ratings and promotions,\u201d Mr.\nMcCarran added.\nChairman Bulow of the Senate Civil\nService Committee returned Saturday\nwith t,he announcement he would fa\nvor the $1,200 minimum bill. Consid-\neration of the McCarran measure was\nput off at the last session at the re\nquest' of the Budget Bureau, which\nstated the administration was study\ning the whole subject of pay and other\npersonnel questions.\nm\u2014---\nJ. W. ANDERSON,\nATTORNEY, DIES\nPatent Lawyer, Ex-D. C. Resi\ndent, Succumbs in Niagara\nTails. N. Y.\nJames Willoughby Anderson, well\nknown patent lawyer and former resi\ndent of this city, died yesterday in\nNiagara Falls, N. Y., after a long ill\nness. according to word received here.\nMr. Anderson was a graduate of\nCentral High School. Lehigh Univer\nsity and Georgetown University Law\u2019\nSchool. After many years\u2019 service as\nprincipal examiner in the Patent Office,\nhe became a member of the firm of\nDuell, Dunn Anderson, View York\npatent lawyers.\nFor the last four years Mr. Ander\nson had been engaged as adviser on\nmatters of patent law to the Moore\nResearch Service Co. of Niagara\nFalls. He left Washington about 1910.\nA native of Norfolk, he was of dis\ntinguished Virginia ancestry, among\nwhom were early settlers. He was\nthe son of Capt. Edward Willoughby\nAnderson of the Confederate Army.\nHis great grandfather, Col. William\nAnderson, U. S. Marine Corps, served\nwith distinction in the War of 1812,\nand his grandfather, Capt. James\nWilloughby Anderson, U. S. A., was\nkilled in action during the Mexican\nWar.\nMr. Anderson was a former presi\ndent of the Dumbarton Club of\nGeorgetown and a member of the Phi\nGamma Delta Fraternity, the Aztec\nClub of 1847, the New York Patent\nLaw Association, the American Pat\nent Law Association, the American\nInstitute of Mining Engineering and\nthe Chemists\u2019 Club of New York.\nHe wax married to the former Miss\nHeloiae Cobb of Norfolk, who sur\nvives. He also leaves a brother and\nthree sisters. They are George M.\nAnderson, Miss Frances Maud An\nderson nad Mrs. Francis P. Sullivan,\nall of this city, and Mrs. Albert\nGreene Gedney of New York.\nThe funeral will be held here, the\ntime to be announced later. Burial\nwill be in Mount Olivet Cemetery.\n\nParking\nf Continued From First Page.)\nfor which they are set apart, or with\nthe duty of the city authorities to keep\nthem open so their use may be en\njoyed free of nuisances.\nHint New Bans on Parking.\n\"Indeed the time may' be soon at\nhand when it will be necessary to for\nbid altogether the garaging of ve\nhicles on the main highways of Wash\nington City at any time, day or night,\nand we have no doubt of the power\nof the Commissioners under the act\nof Congress to make and enforce such\nregulations.\n\"The contrary view rose out of the\nmistaken idea that the owner of an\nautomobile has a right to make \u2018a\nstable yard of the King\u2019s highway,\u2019\nand loses sight of the fact that the\nreal purpose of building and maintain\ning the streets and roads is to permit\nthe convenient passing and repassing\nof the public free of all obstructions\nwhich diminish this enjoyment. The\npower to regulate the use of the streets\nand highways by restrictions of the\nparking of vehicles is one universally\nrecognized, and its reasonable exercise\nis consistently upheld.\u201d\nThe Commissioners were repre\nsented before the Court of Appeals\nby Corporation Counsel El wood H. Seal\nand his assistants. Vernon E. West\nand James E. Lauderdale,\nSix Newcomers Take Their Seats in Congress\nRALPH A. GAMBLE\nRepublican, of\nNew York.\nDAVE E.\nSATTERFIELD, Jr.,\nDemocrat, of Virginia,\nL. K. ROCKEFELLER,\nRepublican, of\nNew York.\nL. J. CONNERY,\nDemocrat, of\nMassachusetts.\nJOHN E. MILLER,\nDemocrat, of\nArkansas.\nBRUCE BARTON,\nRepublican, of\nNew York.\nBy th\u00bb Auoclttad Preu. I\nSIX new Congressmen\u2014one in\nthe Senate and five in the\nHouse\u2014took office today. Here\nare close-ups of the newcopiers:\nJOHN E. MILLER, Democrat, of\nArkansas: After serving for four\nterms in the House takes the Senate\nseat held by his friend, the late Joseph\nT. Robinson. Tall, slim, spruce, gray\nhaired and soft-spoken. Smokes long\ncigars and is an ardent hunter and\nfisherman. Ran as an independent,\nbut says \u201cMy position as a Democrat\nis unchanged.\u2019*\nBRUCE BARTON, Republican, of\nNew York: Advertising man and\nwriter. Represents the \"silk stocking\u201d\ndistrict of New York City. 8andy\nhair, is graying near the temples;\nsquare-jawed, with broad, stubby\nhands; immaculate in dress. Would\nrepeal a law a week; but says the\nDemocrats are stealing his stuff.\nWidely known as author of \u201cThe Man\nNobody Knows.\u201d\nVirginia\u2019s New Member.\nDAVE E. SATTERFIELD, JR.,\nDemocrat, of Virginia: Tall, muscular,\nwith closely-cropped black hair. Served\n12 years as Commonwealth's attorney\nfor Richmond. Was a naval aviator in\nthe World War. Is a licensed pilot, and\nstill flies as a hobby.\nLAWRENCE J. CONNERY, Demo\ncrat, of Massachusetts: Succeeds his\nbrother, the late William P. Connery,\nJr., whom he served as secretary.\nFought in the Yankee Division during\nthe World War. Stocky, black haired,\nand speaks with a pronounced New\nEngland accent. Says he will ad\nvocate the same type of legislation hU j\nbrother did.\nA Rockefeller Appears.\nLEWI8 K. ROCKEFELLER, Repub\nlican, of New York: Says he is no\nrelation to \u201cthe other Rockefellers\"\nand that this Is the first time the\nname has been on the rolls of Con\ngress. Tall, thin, affable, slightly\ndeaf. Friends say he has a \u201cpoker j\nface.\" About 60 years old. Former'\ndeputy State tax commissioner.\nRALPH A. OAMBLE, Republican,\nof New York: Lawyer and son of a\nformer member of Congress from\nSouth Dakota. Served seven terms In\nthe New York State Assembly. Based\nhis campaign on a plea for local self\ngovernment as against centralization\nof power In Washington.\nCongress\n(Continued From First Page.)\nfor greater security of profits and\nproperty.\n\"For the sake of the nation, I hope\nfor your early action.\u201d\nThe President\u2019s call for national co\noperation came on the heels of rum\nblings from returning members of\nCongress that if the administration\ndid not advance a program to en\ncourage and to assist business, they\nwould initiate such a program them\nselves.\nWhile making it clear that the ad\nministration would co-operate with\nbusiness in every way that was fair\nand constructive, the President did\nnot retreat at all from his program of\nsocial betterment and the Improved\nconditions of all workers.\nThe President did not take a gloomy\nview of the situation, although he did\nnot minimize its dangers. In empha\nsizing the need of co-operation be\ntween the Government and all citizens,\nhe said: \"As never before in our his\ntory, the well-being of those who have\nmuch, as well as those who have less,\ndepends upon a contented society cf\ngoodwill where the goodwill rests 'on\nthe solid foundation that all have\nenough.\u201d\nThe Chief Executive insisted that\n\"this recession need go no further\u201d\nand that \"despite some maladjust\nments which can be corrected! under\nlying condtions are not unfavorable.\u201d\nNo specific taxes were mentioned\nbv the President in his discussion of\ntax revision, neither the undistributed\nprofits tax nor the capital gains tax,\nwhich have been under Are particu\nlaily as hampering business expansion\nand actually causing restriction of ac\ntivity. It was presumed, however, that\nhe had these taxes in mind. They\nhave been under consideration already\nby the House Ways and Means Sub\ncommittee, meeting here for the last\n10 days.\nPresident Roosevelt went Over his\nmessage this morning at the White\nHouse with Vice President Garner,\nSpeaker Bankhead, Senator Barkley\nof Kentucky, leader of the Senate,\nand Representative Rayburn of Texas,\nHouse majority leader.\nThe message was ready for trans\nmission to Congress before noon. The\nSenate, however, took a recess until\n1:30 p.m., after appointing a com\nmittee to inform the President that\nit w'as in session. The House, on\nthe other hand, drove straight ahead,\nafter developing a quorum and ap\npointing a committee to notify the\nPresident. Presumably the notifica\ntion was by telephone. At any rate,\nthe reading of the message was be\ngun in the House not long after\n12:30 p.m.\nMr. Roosevelt abandoned for the\nmoment his usual practice of address\ning in person a Joint meeting of a\nnew session of Congress. The mes\nsage, however, was heard with the\nkeenest interest by the Senators and\nRepresentatives who have returned to\nWashington much exercised over the\nbusiness recession.\nCrowds gathered early In the gal\nleries of the House and Senate to\nwitness the opening of the special\nsession. It was precisely at noon that\nVice President Garner and Speaker\nBankhead rapped the respective houses\nto order. The appointment of com\nmittees to notify the President that\nCongress was in session and ready to\nhear what recommendations he might\nhave was promptly rushed through.\nOne newly-elected Senator, John E.\nMiller of Arkansas, successor to the\nlate leader, Senator ''Joe\u201d Robinson,\ntook the oath of office In the Senate\nand four newly-elected members of\nthe House did the same, including\nBruce Barton of New York.\nThe President's message was far\nmore conservative than the message\nhe delivered in person at the opening\nof the first session of the Seventy\nFifth Congress, last January.\nNo Mention of Courts.\nIn discussing Government aid and\nencouragement for business, the Presi\ndent did not say anything regarding\nfuture regulations of which business\nhas been fearful, though he went right\nahead with his demand for a wages\nand hour law and for the establish\nment of the regional T. V- A.s, which\npublic utilities have considered a drive\non them.\nThe President waa particularly re\ngardful of the small business men\nand the small businesses of the Na\ntion. He declared that attention\nshould be given to lightening the tax\nburdens upon them. These small\nbusinesses, he said, have difficulties\nof financing and distribution which\nare not shared by large corporations.\nThe President also told Congress\nthat the problems of railroads and\nother public utilities \"are receiving\nrenewed examination.\u201d He said that\nsolutions will be difficult \"because of\nthoroughly unsound financing extend\ning over many years.\u201d\nHe made no other reference to legis\nlation for revamping the Federal courts.\nIn discussing the propbsal for crop\ncontrol laws, however, the President\nsaid that \u201cwe must keep in mind the\nConstitution of the United States.\u201d\nWhile vital portions of the A. A. A.\nwere set aside two years ago by the\nSupreme Court, the President point\ned out the court had upheld the so\ncial security act and the Wagner la\nbor relations act.\n\"I believe that the courts them\nselves,\u201d said the President, \u201care com\ning to have increasing regard for the\ntrue nature of the Constitution as a\nbroad charter of democratic govern\nment which can function under the\nconditions of today. I believe that\nCongress can constitutionally write\nan adequate farm act that will be well\nwithin the broad meaning and pur\npose of the Constitution.\nWage BUI Now More Needed.\n\u201cI hope and believe the Supreme\nCourt will not again deny to the farm\ners the protection which it now ac\ncords to others.\u201d\nThe picture of agriculture painted\nby the President was one of hopeless\nness unless there should be real crop\ncontrol exercised Cotton, potato and\ncorn crops so large as to threaten all\nthe producers are being harvested, he\nsaid. \u201cWe must continue in our efforts\ntoward abundance without waste,\" the\nPresident said.\nThe business recession, the Presi\ndent urged, makes legislation to es\ntablish minimum wages and maxi\nmum working hours all the more nec- i\nessary if wage income and purchas-\ning power Is to be maintained. He\ndid not demand immediately a uni- 1\nform standard of wages and hours1\nthroughout the country because of\ndiffering conditions in various sec\ntions. Such a uniform standard, he\ninsisted, should eventually come, so\nthat all parts of the country may have\nequally high living standards.\nTwo Immediate purposes, the Presi\ndent said, are the banning of child\nlabor and the use of the unsound\npractice of communities which seek\nnew industries by proclaiming a sup\nply of cheap labor.\nGreat Shaving Outfit\nTHIS WEEK ONLY\n1 Large Tube Shaving Cream\nor\n1 Jar Brushless Shaving Cream\n25 Double-Edge Blades\n1 Bottle After-Shaving Lotion\n1 Can After-Shaving Talcum\n1 Bottle Hair Tonic\nTotal Value, 80c\nAll for 39C\n3 for $1.05\nWe Deliver 3 or Mere in D. C.\nThe Gibson Co.\n917 G St. N.W.\nWashington, D. C.\nI I\nA A A A\nPRESIDENT BEGINS\nWORK ON BUDGET\nf\nBell, Morgenthau and Cum\nmings Confer With Him\nin Three Parleys.\nBy J. RUSSELL YOUNG.\nWith hU message to the special ses\nsion of Congress out of the way, Pres\nident Roosevelt today turned his at\ntention to the task of whipping into\nshape next year's budget, which will\nbe transmitted to the regular session\nof Congress in January.\nThe President, after weeks of labor\non his message to the special session.\nAnally put his O.K. on the completed\ndraft shortly before last midnight.\nHe had devoted the greater part of\nyesterday to the finishing touches on\nthis important document, and with its\ndelivery to the Congress today he\nplunged into other duties, which have\nbeen more or less put aside during the\nmessage-writing period.\nIn his budget work today, the Pres\nWent was assisted by Daniel W. Bell,\nacting director of the budget. This\nprincipal budget lieutenant sat In on\ntwo conferences, one during the early\nforenoon and another later on, with\nAttorney General Cummlng, who was\nalso present.\nSecretary of the Treasury Morgen\nthau, also one of the President's budget\nlieutenants, conferred with the Pres\nident through the luncheon period\nand a light lunch was served on the\nPresident\u2019s desk.\nThe President conferred also with\nSecretary of Agriculture Wallace,\nwhose crop-control legislation is one\nof the major features in the Presi\ndent\u2019s message to Congress; Secretary\nof the Interior Tckes and Representa\ntive Bulwinkle, Democrat, of North\nCarolina, member of the Interstate\nand Foreign Commerce Committee.\nAuto Painting\n2020 m STREET 0. IV.\nLit Hally\u2019i Da It Right I\nSteamed Connecticut\nSoft Clams\nMaylawar Haiti Black, li\u00ab7 Cana. Ara.\n\u2022LAWYERS\u2019 BRIEFS\n1 COMMERCIAL PRIITIHO\nS ADVERTISIRO SERVICE\nBYRON S. ARAMS\n1 lit 11m St.\nRevolution Impending\nA complete revolution in heating economy seems\nto impend with so many home dwellers changing\nMarlouf* Famous Reading Anthracite\nPreferred because it\u2019s so clean. No dirt, no dust,\nall coal, more heat\u2014the \u201cLaundered\u201d coal. More\neconomical because fewer tons are needed. Save\non coal! Let us send you a ton of this pure coal.\nMarlow Coal Co.\n811 E St. N.W. National 0311\n\u201c79 Years of Good Coal Service\u201d\n\nFURNITURE\n\u201cTHE KENT\u201d DINING SUITE $455\nAll Honduras and African Mahogany\n10 PIECES\n68-inch Buffet Chino Cabinet\n2-Drowef Server 8 ft. Extension Table\n4 Side Chairs 2 Arm Chairs\nAn exquisite dining suite from our\nlarge collection of 18th Century\nEnglish pieces. Of Chippendale style\nhandsomely carved\u2014solid Honduras\nmahogany cabriole legs and ball and\nclaw feet and expertly finished by\nhand. The buffet possesses two lined\ndrawers for silverware and the chairs\nare upholstered in a beautiful soft\nblue self-tone brocaded damask. See\nthis exquisite suite here at once.\ni\nOther Ten-Piece Dining Suites\nPriced as Lew as $195\nMAYER CO.\nSeventh Street Between D and E","height":"31144","width":"22284"}}
